[3.5] Omitted Variables

a)

\[\begin{align*} E(\hat{\beta}_1) &= (X_1'X_1)^{-1}X_1'E(y) \\ & = (X_1'X_1)^{-1}X_1'(X_1\beta_1 + X_2\beta_2) \\ & = \beta_1 + (X_1'X_1)^{-1}X_1'X_2\beta_2 \\ & \neq \beta_1 \end{align*}\]

Thus \(\beta_1\) is biased.



b)

For \(\text{Bias}(\hat{\beta}_1) = 0\), we must have \(X_1'X_2\beta_2 = 0\) for all \(\beta_2\), which holds iff \(X_1'X_2 = O\), i.e., the columns of \(X_1\) are orthogonal to the columns of \(X_2\).




[3.10] Cobb-Douglas Production Function

a) Fit Model

Make log transformation on the Cobb-Douglas production function and get a multiple linear regression model: \[\ln{y} = \ln{\beta_0} + \beta_1\ln{x_1} + \beta_2\ln{x_2} + \ln{\epsilon}\]

fit1 = lm(log(output) ~ log(capital) + log(labor), data = cobbdouglas)
summary(fit1)

b0 = fit1$coefficients[1]
b1 = fit1$coefficients[2]
b2 = fit1$coefficients[3]

Hence we get the fitted model: \[ln{y} = -1.7115 + 0.2076 \times \ln{x_1} + 0.7148 \times \ln{x_2}\] The fit is quite good (\(R^2 =\) 83.78%, \(F =\) 1462). The capital and labor elasticities are 0.2076 and 0.7149, respectively.



b)

We want to test \(H_0: \beta_1 + \beta_2 = 1\). Our test statistic will be \(\hat{\beta}_1 + \hat{\beta}_2 - 1\). Note that \[\text{Var}(\hat{\beta}_1 + \hat{\beta}_2) = \text{Var}(\hat{\beta}_1) + \text{Var}(\hat{\beta}_2) + 2\text{Cov}(\hat{\beta}_1, \hat{\beta}_2)\] and \[\text{SE}(\hat{\beta}_1 + \hat{\beta}_2) = \sqrt{\text{Var}(\hat{\beta}_1 + \hat{\beta}_2)} = \sqrt{\text{Var}(\hat{\beta}_1) + \text{Var}(\hat{\beta}_2) + 2\text{Cov}(\hat{\beta}_1, \hat{\beta}_2)}\] The estimated covariance matrix of (\(\hat{\beta}_1\), \(\hat{\beta}_2\)) computed below using R gives the estimates of the variances of \(\hat{\beta}_i\) (\(i = 0, 1, 2\)) and \(\text{Cov}((\hat{\beta}_i, \hat{\beta}_j))\) (\(i, j = 0, 1 , 2\); \(i \neq j\)).

covMat = vcov(fit1); covMat
##                (Intercept)  log(capital)    log(labor)
## (Intercept)   0.0093529294  0.0009477719 -0.0021749139
## log(capital)  0.0009477719  0.0002954123 -0.0002674770
## log(labor)   -0.0021749139 -0.0002674770  0.0005355372
## SE(b1 + b2)
var_b1 = covMat[2, 2]
var_b2 = covMat[3, 3]
cov_b1b2 = covMat[2, 3]
se = sqrt(var_b1 + var_b2 + 2*cov_b1b2)
## t statistics
tstat = (b1 + b2 - 1)/se
t = qt(0.975, df = fit1$df.residual)

Thus, \[\text{SE}(\hat{\beta}_1 + \hat{\beta}_2) = \sqrt{3e-04 + 5e-04 + 2(-3e-04)} = 0.0172\] Hence the \(t\)-statistic equals \[t = \frac{0.2076 + 0.7148 - 1}{0.0172} = -4.5095 > t_{n - (p + 1), \alpha/2} = 1.9642\] This is obviously significant. So we reject the null hypothesis of constant returns to scale.



c)

fit_full = lm(I(log(output) - log(labor)) ~ I(log(capital) - log(labor)) + log(labor), data = cobbdouglas)

The coefficient of Male will be 0.0231. The coefficient of Purchase will be +0.0938, the coefficient of Advert will change to 0.0388 + 0.0938 = 0.055 and the coefficient of Engg will change to 0.0573 + 0.0938 = 0.0881. Also, the constant term will change to 4.429 0.0231 + 0.0938 = 4.499.



c)

predict(fit3, newdata = data.frame(YrsEm = 8, PriorYr = 10, Education = 12, Gender = "Male", Dept = "Sales", Super = 6), interval = "predict")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 4.618439 4.504974 4.731904

Thus the predicted salary is \(10^{4.618} = 41495\) with the PI \(= [10^{4.505}, 10^{4.732}] = [31989, 53951]\). Note that the PI is very wide.



d)

The coefficient of Engg is highly nonsignificant when Purchase is used as the reference category because there is not a significant difference between the salaries of employees in Engg and Purchase. But when the reference category is changed to Sales, there is a significant difference between the salaries of employees in Engg and Sales (the coefficient changes from 0.0573 to +0.0881). So if the coefficient of a dummy variable is nonsignificant, all it tells you is that category is not significantly different from the reference category.



e)

Gender can be dropped as a predictor variable. However, Dept cannot be dropped since at least one of its categories (namely, Sales) has a significant coefficient. Generally, it is recommended that the categories be left unpooled. If the nonsignificant categories, Advert and Engg, are pooled with the reference category, Purchase, then the interpretation of the model may become difficult.




[4.4] College GPA and entrance test scores

a)

The fitted values and the normal Q-Q plots are shown below. The fitted values plot is funnel-shaped indicating heteroscedasticity and the normal plot also shows non-normality. The funnel is expanding linearly suggesting logarithmic transformation.

fit4 = lm(GPA ~ Verbal + Math + I(Verbal^2) + I(Math^2) + I(Verbal*Math), data = GPA)

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
## normal plot of residuals
plot(fit4, which = 2)
## fitted values plot of residuals
plot(fit4, which = 1)



b)

The same plots are shown below when log(GPA) is used as the response variable. Residuals vs.fitted values plot does not indicate any heteroscedasticity although the plot appears quadratic. This is due to the quadratic terms being not included in the model which we know are significant from Example 3.8. The normal plot is slightly improved. Overall, the logarithmic transformation gives a somewhat improved fit.

fit5 = lm(log(GPA) ~ Verbal + Math + I(Verbal^2) + I(Math^2) + I(Verbal*Math), data = GPA)

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
## normal plot of residuals
plot(fit5, which = 2)
## fitted values plot of residuals
plot(fit5, which = 1)
